+# Equine Gateway v2 — Multi-device registry
+
+This step upgrades the protocol-v1 gateway from one hard-coded tracker to a
+compile-time registry of trackers. The tracker firmware and the protocol-v1
+wire format are unchanged.
+
+## Configure trackers
+
+Edit `equine_gateway_registry.h`:
+
+```cpp
+static const GatewayTrackerConfig GATEWAY_TRACKERS[] = {
+  {"wera", "Wera", true, true},
+  {"hugo", "Hugo", false, false},
+};
+```
+
+Fields:
+
+1. `id`: stable canonical identifier. It produces the public 64-bit routing
+   hash. Do not reuse an ID for another physical tracker.
+2. `name`: human-readable display name.
+3. `accepts_legacy_lora`: maps old packets without a device hash to this
+   tracker. At most one entry may enable it.
+4. `publish_legacy_mqtt_aliases`: additionally publishes `horse/<id>/...`
+   topics while old clients migrate.
+
+`GATEWAY_ID` identifies the receiver node independently from the trackers.
+
+## Routing
+
+Protocol-v1 history frames are routed by `device_id_hash` to the matching
+registry entry. Unknown hashes are rejected and do not receive an ACK.
+
+Legacy packets contain no identity. They are accepted only when exactly one
+registry entry has `accepts_legacy_lora=true`.
+
+## MQTT topics
+
+Each tracker publishes to its own canonical topic:
+
+```text
+equine/v1/trackers/<device_hash>/state
+equine/v1/trackers/<device_hash>/availability
+```
+
+The receiver has a separate LWT topic:
+
+```text
+equine/v1/gateways/<gateway_hash>/availability
+```
+
+Home Assistant discovery uses the gateway LWT. Per-tracker availability topics
+are also published for applications and migration, but only the gateway topic
+is guaranteed to become `offline` after an ungraceful receiver disconnect.
+
+Each state event contains:
+
+- `device_id`, `device_name`, and `device_hash`
+- `gateway_id` and `gateway_hash`
+- `point_id = <device_hash>:<boot_id>:<seq>`
+- position, distance, battery, RSSI, sequence and protocol versions
+
+`point_id` gives servers and apps a stable key for deduplicating the same point
+when several gateways publish it.
+
+## Per-tracker deduplication
+
+Every tracker has an independent NVS namespace derived from 56 bits of its
+public hash. The full 64-bit hashes and shortened NVS namespaces are checked
+for collisions at startup.
+
+The old single-tracker `gateway` NVS cursor is automatically migrated to the
+entry marked `accepts_legacy_lora`.
+
+A packet is ACKed only after:
+
+- the complete packet structure is valid,
+- every new point has been published to the canonical MQTT topic, and
+- duplicates have already been published according to that tracker's cursor.
+
+If MQTT fails part-way through a packet, already published points remain in the
+cursor, no ACK is sent, and the next retry skips those points before continuing.
+
+## Local gateway API
+
+The web interface now shows the tracker registry, last-seen age, RSSI and dedup
+cursor. Machine-readable registry state is available at:
+
+```text
+GET /api/v1/trackers
+```
+
+## Upgrade sequence
+
+1. Flash this gateway firmware.
+2. Keep the current protocol-v1 tracker firmware unchanged.
+3. Verify Wera still publishes and receives ACKs.
+4. Add further tracker entries and flash those trackers with their own canonical
+   IDs.
+
+## Deliberately deferred
+
+This step does not yet provide persistent editable configuration, onboarding,
+encryption, or relay forwarding. Simultaneous ACKs from multiple gateways that
+hear the same LoRa frame also require a later coordination/relay design. MQTT
+consumers should already deduplicate using `point_id`.
